			<div class="content" id="post-content-2572775">
									

<p>And here we are. Finally. If you'll excuse me, I'm going to go pass out now. Will write more later.</p>
<p>Edit:</p>
<p>It's somewhat ironic that, as a nominally successful author on this site, I increasingly find myself at a loss for words. Perhaps writing for the site is sapping my &quot;talent&quot;, a la the classic 1996 film Space Jam&#8230; nope, I still can't say that with a straight face.</p>
<p>I suppose I should start with the beginning. Rather obvious starting point in hindsight, wouldn't you say?</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;A&nbsp;'Brief'&nbsp;History&nbsp;Lesson</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;TL;DR&nbsp;People&nbsp;wrote&nbsp;things,&nbsp;I&nbsp;was&nbsp;one&nbsp;of&nbsp;them</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>The seeds for Third Law were planted as far back as 2014, with the Groups of Interest Contest. I did not participate in this contest<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-185131-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-185131-1')">1</a></sup>, but A Random Day &#8212; the man who would become my collaborator and partner in creating this canon &#8212; did. He was part of the ill-fated Prometheus Labs team that ended up not placing in the contest after most of its members bailed. However, the PL team &#8212; which at this point was essentially just ARD &#8212; did give us the PL GOI format.</p>
<p>Fast forward a little bit more than a year, and we find rookie author GreenWolf &#8212; that's me, in case you haven't been paying attention &#8212; coming off the high of his first massively successful article<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-185131-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-185131-2')">2</a></sup> and eagerly looking for the next big thing to write. This is one of those moments that Terry Pratchett referred to as the trousers of time &#8212; a point in history where the result of a single decision makes all the difference. I asked TwistedGears what I should do for my next article, and he told me to write something about Prometheus Labs. Intrigued, I spent the afternoon going over what PL articles currently existed on the site, which is how I discovered the PL GOI format. I was instantly won over by the format, and set about writing my own. Then I wrote another. <span style="text-decoration: line-through;">Then I wrote a terrible tale based off of the second GOI format that no one can prove ever existed.</span></p>
<p>By this point, I was completely and absolutely in love with Prometheus Labs as a GOI, and was determined to revitalize them. I wanted to change the site's perception of them as a group of failures who had every project go horribly wrong, instead depicting them as researchers working on the cutting edge of science &#8212; both anomalous and mundane &#8212; with all of the risks and rewards that entails. In retrospect, such an endeavor was almost certainly too ambitious, especially for a rookie writer. And yet, here we are.</p>
<p>When the MTF contest rolled around, I immediately teamed up with ARD with the intent of doing an MTF that focused on Prometheus Labs and the Foundation's interaction with them. We added sirpudding and TyGently to our ranks. It was this team that was responsible for laying the foundations for what would become Third Law, and it was during our planning meetings that Third Law first became something more substantial than a collection of vaguely formed ideas inside my head.</p>
<p>Over the following months, Third Law would both grow and change, expanding in focus and scope from just a PL canon to a canon about paratech, viewed through the lens of PL. I setup a proto-hub for the canon on the sandbox site, which would gradually grow over the following months as more details of the setting were fleshed out and more articles were written for Third Law. And it will hopefully continue to grow as more authors write articles for Third Law.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>So, with the history lesson out of the way, I suppose I should answer the inevitable question: What exactly <em>is</em> this canon for?</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;What&nbsp;is&nbsp;this?</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;'This'&nbsp;is&nbsp;a&nbsp;pronoun.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>First, let me tell you what Third Law is <em>not</em>.</p>
<ul>
<li>It is not a canon dedicated exclusively to Prometheus Labs.</li>
<li>It is not a canon dedicated exclusively to Apotheosis.</li>
<li>It is not a canon dedicated to the color blue.</li>
<li>It is not a pipe.</li>
</ul>
<p>Third Law is a canon focusing on paratech &#8212; on its development, its regulation, its use, its effects, and on the people who do or are involved in these things. It takes as its fundamental axioms the fact that the anomalous <em>can</em> be scientifically studied and eventually understood, and that this parascience drives a thriving industry and market just behind the Veil. Naturally, this canon will have a strong focus on Prometheus Labs, as they are/were the single largest manufacturer of paratech, but it is not solely about them. In fact, at the time of this writing, PL only directly appears in two of the tales for this canon.</p>
<p>TL;DR: This is a canon dedicated to magitech and science fantasy (in the sense that the fantastical elements can be studied as a science). It assumes a large anomalous world, a weak but still intact Veil, and the strength of the scientific method in the face of the unknown and incomprehensible.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Finally, I'd like to extend my thanks and appreciation to everyone who helped make this canon possible:</p>
<ul>
<li>A Random Day, without whom there would be no Third Law, nor an abundance of all caps GOI format articles. You've been an essential part of the development of this canon since before its conception, and I'm glad to have had the opportunity to collaborate with you.</li>
<li>TyGently, don't discount the importance of your contributions. You've been a constant and valuable source of ideas, criticism, and support for me and for this canon.</li>
<li>sirpudding, whose input during the MTF contest helped shape the fundamental nature of this canon. Without you and your ideas, both Apotheosis and Third Law wouldn't be nearly as good as they are now.</li>
<li>Aiden Eldritch, the individual who finally pushed this into official canon status with an excellent cyberpunk tale reminiscent of <em>Snow Crash</em>. Your support and contributions are no less essential for having come later, and I'm glad to have you on board. I look forward to seeing you post Operation Llewyn Dark.</li>
<li>TwistedGears, who provided the initial impetus that led to me writing PL stuff, and eventually Third Law, and who's criticism during the early stages of the hub planning and world-building pushed this away from being an exclusively PL canon, a change in scope which has only been an improvement.</li>
<li>Randomini, a bountiful source of inspiration, criticism, and technical help with the finer aspect of CSS.</li>
<li>Conwell, who I believe has helped critique every tale written for this canon so far. I'd also like to thank you for providing the site with Anderson Robotics, a GOI that has been an amazing addition to the wiki in general, and a source of some amazing stories for this canon.</li>
<li>Dr Kens, for assistance with some of the technical and aesthetic elements of the CSS theme for this. Also for that kicking rad mock movie poster for Apotheosis you made during the MTF contest.</li>
<li>minmin, your criticism was invaluable to the tales in this canon.</li>
<li>Jekeled, your crit was incredibly helpful too.</li>
<li>Decibelle, for your support and suggestions.</li>
<li>And to everyone who helped critique a tale or skip or goi-format for Third Law. If your name isn't up there, it's only because I'm terrible at remembering names.</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Scientia Potentia Est</em></p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-185131-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-185131-1')">1</a>. Although I was a member of the site at the time, I had drifted away and would not return until the following year, and wouldn't author a successful article until that November.</div>
